@AldinDynamics You're very welcome! Thank you all for giving me a solid reason to dust off the HMD! ^^
RT @CrimsonZen: So, a lack of rich motion-controlled gameplay has left me somewhat jaded about #VR. So it wasn't until now that I got off m…

I suspect a great physical VR action game is going to make players stand their ground and "protect" their play space.

It's one of the core beliefs I held when making LSA: you can incentivize leg movement without tracking legs - and that gets your whole body into the game!

Some of that work is going to take more devs like Aldin to take risks braving the largely unexplored territory of 6DOF motion controls. But...

I also think more developers & gamers are going to need to open their mind to action games that embrace alternative movement paradigms.

There are other parts of the game I could review, but I'll leave it at this since it's what I care about.

All-in-all Aldin did a damn good job - especially if you stack them up against other attempts at spellcasting. But it's very clear there's a lot more work to be done.

Spectral Orb: ★★☆☆ So, it's solid when it works. It's hard to aim but that's part of the charm.

Unfortunately the spell is hamstrung because the ritual for throwing a Spectral Orb ends up conjuring a Spectral Blade 80% of the time. Almost feels like a bug (Index only?)

Tornado: ★★★★ This is the Telekinesis your Telekinesis could smell like. Hilariously, it's the best defensive option in NM. It's a super reliable one-handed Neutron Orb. Absolutely fantastic for making space. Send it down a trap hallway while you advance for protection!

Lightning Bolt: ★★★☆ Dope, in principle. Consistent and satisfying ritual during both preparation and casting, and the visuals are excellent. But damn is it hard to aim. I wish it either did more damage or snapped to targets in a wider cone.

Neutron Explosion: ★★☆☆ Consistent? Yes. Useful? Absolutely not. It's rare that I'd want to blow up my orb for melee damage when I could just as easily throw it forward and get basically the same effect. Effectively it's another too-slow defensive maneuver.

Neutron Orb (cont.): Neutron Orb feels great because it's got visual and aural cues mid-ritual, so it works even without haptics for the charge-up. It always feels good to know you're "doing it right".

Neutron Orb: ★★★★ Now that's more like it! Once I figured it out, activation was super consistent, and the payoff always made the ritual worth it.

My only recommendation - and this goes for many spells in NM - is to add distinct haptics that kick in *before* the cast point.

Sonic Scream: ★★☆☆ Oof, I wanted to like this one - requiring gesture + voice was smart - but the input was too demanding. Brief shouts ("toof!") didn't work, and I'm not gonna hold a sustained scream in an apartment complex. Might be better if I wasn't concerned about that.

Spectral Blade: ★★☆☆ It's a punching dagger. Unlike Instant Shield, it's easy to conjure. Too easy, in fact. Too often I would use Conjure to "bank" Magic in a hand as prep, only to overwrite it with Spectral Blade while running.

It's also got all the usual VR sword problems

Instant Shield (cont.): A good shield spell should make you feel safe. Instant Shield does not. Compounded with the AI/Telepath retreating issues I mentioned earlier, you're left with no good panic button..

The damn thing functions better used as a Blade with a bigger hitbox.

Instant Shield (cont.): Other problems:

* If you accidentally release grip (very common on Index) it evaporates instantly. I found myself squeezing hard
* It doesn't block projectiles while I'm in a Telepath slide, which makes it useless for trap hallways.

Instant Shield (cont.): I could write an essay on this spell. A spell called "Instant Shield" really should be a reliable defensive maneuver, except it's anything but. The spell takes too long to perform, too long to take effect, and too many hands for how crappy the result is.

Instant Shield: ★☆☆☆ 

VR gamedevs. please. I am BEGGING you to stop making buckler-style shields. They suck! There's nothing fun about determining the correct wrist contortion to hold the damn thing at, and they're ALWAYS too small. Consider a force field instead.
Telekinesis (cont): I also found myself annoyed at how difficult it was to gently pull items toward me. However, I do appreciate that you need a direct hit to manipulate larger enemies.

Telekinesis: ★★☆☆ A mixed bag. Useful for grabbing items, but I couldn't trust it in combat. Particles will stick to stuff even after the Control window ends, causing confusion as to why I couldn't grab to activate Telekinesis.

Cast Magic & Control: ★★★☆ I've not been the biggest fan of "push to launch" fireballs for two reasons: they aren't super satisfying to perform, and they're imprecise. WotW fixes the second problem with the grab-to-control system, which lets you course-correct comfortably.

Onto the spells! (For reference, I played on Index controllers.)

Gather Magic: ★★★★ Pretty much nailed it with this gesture. Which is good, since it's basically the foundation of all the other spells. It's quick, reliable, and satisfying.

Telepath (cont.): This problem is compounded by WotW's enemy AI, which has no concept of your room boundaries. Retreating from melee attackers sucks immensely.

All that said, Telepath is a rather clever and flexible system that does its best with the challenges of open movement.

Telepath (cont.): ...it also goes to show that even once you beat nausea, you're still stuck with all the other problems inherent to open movement VR games, such as corner lock. Freedom of digital movement causes fear of physical movement.

https://t.co/QHNeAZJZkH

Telepath: As someone that gets motion sick very easily, this might be my favorite open movement locomotion system. They clearly put a lot of work into the design and it shows.

That being said...

Voice Recognition ring (not technically motion control, but a "natural" control in a sense):

It's cute. Points for the contextually-aware "point and speak" interactions, but at its heart, it's still like any other verbal CLI. Might be more fun if you've never used voice controls

Since I've been too preoccupied to work on my own VR projects, I'll break the relevant bits I played in WotW:NM down mechanic-by-mechanic, and pretend like my peanut-gallery thoughts represent a genuine contribution to the industry.

So, a lack of rich motion-controlled gameplay has left me somewhat jaded about #VR. So it wasn't until now that I got off my butt to try out #WaltzOfTheWizard: Natural Magic, and I've got thoughts on @AldinDynamics' refreshingly whole-hearted swing in the right direction! 1/?

For now I'm settling for jotting some notes and sending some tweets to at least iron out the concepts in my head. I figure if a clear project emerges from all that, I could break ground on it, but until then, I'll just keep dreaming.

So I've been wondering—what do I really want to ship? A complete game? A playable demo? A video showcase? Does it matter if I get paid? Does it matter if other people play it?

I'm not sure I know what I want yet. All I feel clearly is that I want these ideas explored.

What I frustratingly found was that little else in the development process was anywhere near as satisfying as the actual gameplay design. Designing a better fireball was great, but there's an entire game around those fireballs that needed to be designed, in order to ship.

What excites me most is the prospect of gameplay where optimal play is equal parts physical and mental, engaging every cell of your body to evoke an immensely satisfying feeling of command.

I want players to feel like a true master of their art, from the inside out. Somatically.
In working on LSA, I was most driven when prototyping each of my new "weapons." Each one was a chance to invent and test a new style of combat, each a new physical form of play.
What Nintendo has been able to accomplish with limited hardware has been inspiring, and to me, the Vive/Rift generation of VR has been a new opportunity to explore that space more deeply.

When I was working on LSA, I was eager to explore the uncharted waters of deeply physical gameplay.

I admired Nintendo's forays into that unknown, with their experiments on the Wii and other platforms. Let the record show I actually *liked* the motion controls in Skyward Sword!

Been taking a little bit of time between holiday visits and Endwalker binging to meditate on my relationship with game design.

While I'm currently working on a 2d indie game with a friend and haven't touched VR in months, I find my daydreams always take me back to what could be.

Some people *like* juggling lots of mechanics on the fly (me!) I like my games "spicy" in this sense because they give you the space and opportunity to come up with clever & clutch decisions in the heat of the moment.

This lack of "spice" is why I've gotten bored of VR, as well

Dota? Spicy. Monster Hunter? Spicy. TWEWY? Hella spicy.

I think I like "spicy" because everyone has a unique taste level when it comes to spiciness, and that's okay! I feel words like "complex" are a bit loaded because there's this idea that complexity is inferior to elegance

I wish there was a term for fast-paced video games with lots and lots of interlocking mechanics. Something distinct from but not mutually exclusive with "deep" (takes a long time to master) and "complex" (lots of interlocking mechanics, regardless of game speed).

Maybe... spicy?

Like, this thread took me two dedicated hours to write. Ugh.

It wouldn't be so bad if I could pay someone a living wage - that way I could be comfortable they're guaranteed *something*. But I don't think I have that kind of cash.

All-in-all I should probably just accept who I am, and try to just find an artist to work with, but... this gives me extreme anxiety.

I'd need to find someone passionate about the goal, but I'm most worried I'll come off as a "lazy perfectionist" that can't pull his own weight.

There's a lot of advice out there about how to learn to draw. (Practice!) But the fact is, for me, drawing *hurts* in ways I still struggle to describe.

It's hard enough for me to learn things I'm not passionate about, but the dissonance of drawing ugly things is unbearable

My ADHD, like many others, thrives on immediate feedback loops. And I love the feelings of joy people share when they try the things I've made!

Unfortunately, without visual appeal, it takes an arm and a leg to get anyone to try these things out.

My true passion, I think, is the intersection of gameplay design and human-computer interaction. I love the feelings of power & adrenaline given by a well-designed action game, and through gameplay systems is where I can best express my creativity. https://t.co/MLgNmfgPjU

I constantly feel like I'm one "hop" away from self-actualization. It feels like there are 4 or 5 potential solutions to the equation (such as suddenly becoming rich), none of which I have a reliable path to acquiring.

One of those solutions is to figure out "How To Art."

Still can't focus on work despite this morning's Big Emotions passing through so maybe I'll try sharing one of the feelings I've been struggling with?

I hate to admit this, but I'm envious of other ADHDers with a penchant for the visual arts.

But—as with Artifact—if Valve cant pull off "Gen 1 VR game," we need a BIG shakeup.

HL:A will be to "Gen 1 VR Game" as Artifact is to "Traditional CCG"

There are like 3 or 4 threads I want to pull in VR game design right now?  

But like... money.

The end goal here is simple: make players *feel anime.*

* Slow, embodied skill "performances" make you feel cool and powerful
* Interaction timings incentivize YELLING THE NAME OF YOUR SKILL over VoIP
* Necessary communication makes players feel the power of friendship!

Here's the interaction:
0s: P1 starts using Frost Blade.
1s: P1» "Readying Frost Blade!"
2s: P2 reacts; starts using Heavy Crush.
4s: P1 completes FB cast, effect starts playing.
5s: FB applies "frostbite"
6s: P2 finishes HC during frostbite, triggers Cold Snap skillchain bonus.

Let's make up a 2-player skillchain, like Frost Blade->Heavy Crush. Design the embodiment so that these skills take 4 seconds of motion, and by lining the impact times up carefully, the second hit completes a combo started by the first.

Anyway... fingers crossed. After taking some time off from doing heavy dev on LSA, I'm realizing how much work I put into it & how it deserves a better shot at success than what I've been able to give it thus far.

I'm anxious a working with Oculus would push LSA away from that essence. Worse, I'm paranoid that Oculus's preference for "visual over physical" has made its community expect "specific things" of VR games.

It's partly paranoia—but kids do better than VR peeps when trying LSA.

All of that is rather discouraging when I've worked so hard to make @LightStrikeVR embrace full-motion physicality that makes VR special. I've no interest in compromising that facet of the design, as it would cause complete structural failure.

Oculus historically hasn't been receptive to games contingent on high-range embodiment. The DK1 shipped with a gamepad. Carmack doesn't believe gamers want to use their bodies. The approval process requires support for 2-camera setups, & the new gen can't really track behind you.

Hopefully I'll get the chance to demo Light Strike Array at #OC6. It's probably the last big crowd that hasn't gotten to experience it... and that's mostly my fault for assuming the game wouldn't be a good fit for the crowd.

Hopefully I get the chance to prove myself wrong!
